<Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None< /response><Date>1474402390524< /Date><name>Ron Wenger< /name>< Text>
I played the course for the first time while visiting family on Friday September 16.  The course was in overall good shape.  Some of the greens are very big with nice curves.  Noted the lip of the cups were not groomed which caused several missed putts. You have to hit almost dead center to sink a putt.  Also noted numerous ball marks and debris on the greens that needed repair to no fault of the course greens keeper.  (Fix your ball marks guys and gals!!)    Front nine featured some very narrow fairways which proved unfriendly to a fade or draw.  The back nine opened up some and the water holes provided a fair challenge.  Overall I would play the course again when in the area.  A suggestion would be to provide a map of the course, of some signage, that would assist a person, not from the area, with finding the holes on the back nine.  Had to use a number of paved streets to navigate and if I were not with a local, I would still be lost.< /Text>

< user>
118284410923417295185< /user>
< name>
Wristan</name>
<time>1555088172859</time><rate>3</rate>< text>
I've been going here since late 2016 and I like to say I thought everything was going well. On 3/29/19 I received a bill for balances I didn't even know about. I've always checked in with Nikki and asked, "Do I owe anything?" Only a few times have I paid any amount out of my pocket.
I was told by Nikki, "We try to always be patient as well when we are waiting for claims to be processed and paid. It does sometimes take a year or two."

If claims took this long to get processed then there would be a lot of angry clients/patients wondering why they were receiving backlog of procedures owed from nearly 2 and half years ago. Before any procedure is done, the patients should be given an estimate of how much will be out of the patients pocket and what the insurance will cover. These total may change, but at least the patient is aware of what at cost to them.

Not once over these two year when I had filling did Nikki tell me any sort of estimate on the way out before or even after procedures. At my former dental places they always told me estimates or if I will be possibly needing to pay anything. You can not just slam a patient with a bill that's several hundred dollars that could've been paid over a time frame of 30 month(10/4/2016 - 3/29/2019).

The staff is friendly overall and everything else has been fine. I've personally only seen Nikki as the only receptionist and I think this could've been part of the reason due to the delay. I don't think the Insurance dropped the ball. Regardless, there were estimated balances in the system and despite claim being processed or not, I should have been made aware of them.

Using another dental office as an example, before they do any procedure on patients, they print and estimate with base price, how much the insurances will possibly cover and what possible final out of pocket is to the patient. This document need to be signed stating that the patient agrees with the out of pocket estimate and to the procedure.

All agreements that I ever done in Harbor Dental was verbal, this is bad since people can have a hard time remembering if they agreed to the procedure. There should always be a physical copy of work being done and a copy being given to the patients at the time. This keeps both parties ending up in a bad situation. I hope going forward physical copy of the work are drawn up and a signature is required agreeing to the out of pocket cost to the patient.

I seem to be the only one this has happened too, but if this happen a lot I don't think to many clients/patients would be happy to be hit with a large bill years down the road. If that were to happen not many people would stick around. To anyone thinking of going to Harbor Dental, they're fine, but I would suggest a print out of your patient transaction after every visit and check it there's any past due balances.< /text>

Nice place to play badminton but gets crowded during evenings< /review>
</record>

<text>I found this to be one of more likable Bintang gyms.

- It's very spacious and there are more courts here than at any other gym I've seen
- You get to play 30-45 minutes before the next group can kick you off. (Unfortunately, this also means potentially longer wait times)
- Unlike nearly all other badminton gyms, this location has water fountains. Thank you, Good Guy Milpitas Bintang!
- The managers also don't seem to be as picky about kicking everyone out immediately after closing time (Shame on Sunnyvale Bintang)

Of course, it doesn't come without downsides:
- It's extremely crowded between 7-9pm
- Bathrooms aren't exceptionally clean, which is a bit disappointing since the gym isn't that old
- It gets very warm because there's little ventilation

Price is $9 at night unless you're part of some special group that gets in for $6. I see someone else here complained about the $9 price. That's actually on par with most other gyms in the area. That's not to say it isn't expensive, but welcome to the Bay Area. Get used to paying an arm and a leg for entertainment and leisure. At least here water is free and not $2 a bottle.< /text>< Gmap_id>

<user_name>Ceci Gonzalez<//user_name>< Time>
1581231295716</Time>
<Text>I came here on a Saturday with a friend who kept raving about the place. I waited about an hour or so and ordered at a kiosk and paid with my card. That to me feels very modern and pays homage to how Japan also uses kiosks for customers to order and pay. Once we were seated down, the waitress quickly served us our waters and asked if we needed anything and was overall very sweet and welcoming. The ramen came about ten min later or so, not too bad. Definetely recommend coming here on a weekday, not during lunch hours of course, especially if you are impatient. Once I tried the broth, I knew it was worth the wait. I ordered the classic Tenkatsu ramen and it had a great depth of flavor. I added an the egg and it was flavorful and creamy. On the tables, there is seaweed, garlic and a garlic press, chili oil and chili flakes to make your ramen taste even better. I love spice, so I added the chili oil and it made my soup even more amazing. Would definetely come back, but when it is less busy which is why I only gave 4 stars.</Text>< user_id>
115549631072100182733< /user_id>

<GmapID>0x80c2bf2ab548da49:0xb5e3296938e1d959</GmapID>< Review>
I came here on a Saturday with a friend who kept raving about the place. I waited about an hour or so and ordered at a kiosk and paid with my card. That to me feels very modern and pays homage to how Japan also uses kiosks for customers to order and pay. Once we were seated down, the waitress quickly served us our waters and asked if we needed anything and was overall very sweet and welcoming. The ramen came about ten min later or so, not too bad. Definetely recommend coming here on a weekday, not during lunch hours of course, especially if you are impatient. Once I tried the broth, I knew it was worth the wait. I ordered the classic Tenkatsu ramen and it had a great depth of flavor. I added an the egg and it was flavorful and creamy. On the tables, there is seaweed, garlic and a garlic press, chili oil and chili flakes to make your ramen taste even better. I love spice, so I added the chili oil and it made my soup even more amazing. Would definetely come back, but when it is less busy which is why I only gave 4 stars.< /Review>

< Review>
Good spot, hip crowd. At peak times expect a wait of up to 40 to 60 minutes for a table. No reservations, no name on  list. You queue up and wait until it's your turn to order on the iPad. Then they seat you.

Very noisey inside, so not great for a date. Ramen is good but I would not call it amazing. Worth a visit if in area.< /Review>

<gmapID>0x80c2bf2ab548da49:0xb5e3296938e1d959<//gmapID></record>
</dataset><record>
<Text>The ramen is definitely authentic but overpriced when you start to add different sides that should come with the ramen, such as a seasoned egg. For two people and a couple of sides and drinks, we paid over $70. The "Soul Ramen" has the right amount of spice, savory and sweetness, so the flavor profile was there. But one unforgivable across the other items we ordered: the kurobuta pork. It's tough, not nearly as tender and juicy as other ramen establishments. The pork bun was massive but messy and wet, overly sweet and again used tough pork meat. We loved the fried rice, which was flavored exceptionally well. Hated to rate this place low for what it is, but definitely did not feel the value for the price point. Parking situation is horrendous; good luck finding parking.</Text>< Rate>
3<//Rate>

< rate>
5<//rate>
< review>
If you‚Äôre a fan of ramen, this is a must-try. Vegans and gluten-free eaters can have a field day here. Lots of options and ways to make your ramen suit you. I‚Äôve had all but the chicken and I‚Äôm a huge fan of the vegan ramen even though I‚Äôm not vegan.

Bowls cost $12 -$14 and you can customize meat (chicken, chashyu pork or tofu) add extra noodles or eggs to your order.

There‚Äôs about 6 parking spots out front, shared by 4 other stores so chances are they are taken, but worth a drive by. Plenty of street parking.

There‚Äôs usually a line at night stretching out the door. The line moves, I‚Äôve never had to wait over an hour.

Add fresh garlic with a garlic press, fresh sesame with a sesame grinder, seaweed, chili flakes and chili oil at your table.

Indoor and outdoor seating available. All items can be made to-go. All ramen noodles made in-house.</review>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
I ate here a while ago, but I was too tired to write a review, while I was at the restaurant. Just in case you don't know, your experience here begins with ordering your food on iPads situated on the far left wall. I've been here so many times that the ordering process is 2nd nature. A machine underneath the iPad prints out your receipt though a slit in the wall. At this point, present your receipt to the cashier/host and they will lead you to your seat. The place was packed, but she still managed to find seating for us outside.

I recommend the Bold Ramen with extra tonkatsu noodles. If you have an appetite leftover, then the fried rice is also a winner!  Our food was delivered promptly and our water glasses were also kept full. Some places become inattentive, once they deliver your food. Not here. We were given great attention and we really enjoyed our experience! This place is a must if you are in mid-city.< /review>

<gmap_id>0x80c2bf2ab548da49:0xb5e3296938e1d959< /gmap_id>< review>
I came here on a Saturday with a friend who kept raving about the place. I waited about an hour or so and ordered at a kiosk and paid with my card. That to me feels very modern and pays homage to how Japan also uses kiosks for customers to order and pay. Once we were seated down, the waitress quickly served us our waters and asked if we needed anything and was overall very sweet and welcoming. The ramen came about ten min later or so, not too bad. Definetely recommend coming here on a weekday, not during lunch hours of course, especially if you are impatient. Once I tried the broth, I knew it was worth the wait. I ordered the classic Tenkatsu ramen and it had a great depth of flavor. I added an the egg and it was flavorful and creamy. On the tables, there is seaweed, garlic and a garlic press, chili oil and chili flakes to make your ramen taste even better. I love spice, so I added the chili oil and it made my soup even more amazing. Would definetely come back, but when it is less busy which is why I only gave 4 stars.<//review>

<userid>110154227967498928379</userid><username>Shun Cheung Ip</username>< Date>
1473296775215< /Date>
< rate>
5< /rate>
< Review>
The ramen here is really good. As a spicy food lover, bold ramen is the best. Try to finish the broth and you will be surprised! If you get the ramen without egg, you should order one because it is delicious! The small bowl of fried rice is pretty good too. They have a really good system for you to order. Instead of waiting to get your seat to order, you just have to use one of the 4 tablets they provided at the entrance to order and pay (you can pay later by cash). You can customize your ramen like the spicyness, type of ramen, garlic amount, and so on. They will process your order after they assign you a table. People who work there are so nice and friendly. Interesting thing is they have free corn, and you can get a lot! Just remember to order it from the side dishes/ extra tab.< /Review>

<text>Went Saturday afternoon around 2:30 and waited about 15 minutes to be seated. While you wait in line, you use iPads on the wall to place your order and to pay. I had the Bold Ramen (mild spice) and a side of Pork Chashu Rice. Both were terrific, though the tastiness of the rice was a surprise.

Parking would be a pain during peak times. We parked along the street about 50 yards away.

Once you brave the (occasionally long) wait, Tatsu is a great place to get your ramen fix. The venue is open with some limited seating and the restaurant is lively. The ramen is very well seasoned and can be customized to your liking when you order by tablet while in line.

I would advise against driving in as parking can be a bit hard to come by.  The experience of coming here is well worth your time.<//review>

0x80c2bf2ab548da49:0xb5e3296938e1d959< /Gmap_id>
< Review>
The ramen here is really good. As a spicy food lover, bold ramen is the best. Try to finish the broth and you will be surprised! If you get the ramen without egg, you should order one because it is delicious! The small bowl of fried rice is pretty good too. They have a really good system for you to order. Instead of waiting to get your seat to order, you just have to use one of the 4 tablets they provided at the entrance to order and pay (you can pay later by cash). You can customize your ramen like the spicyness, type of ramen, garlic amount, and so on. They will process your order after they assign you a table. People who work there are so nice and friendly. Interesting thing is they have free corn, and you can get a lot! Just remember to order it from the side dishes/ extra tab.<//Review>

< Text>
Once you brave the (occasionally long) wait, Tatsu is a great place to get your ramen fix. The venue is open with some limited seating and the restaurant is lively. The ramen is very well seasoned and can be customized to your liking when you order by tablet while in line.

I would advise against driving in as parking can be a bit hard to come by.  The experience of coming here is well worth your time.</Text>

< text>
I came here a number of years ago when they first opened and didn't like the broth they served then. I recently stopped back in and I'm so glad I did the Hippie broth is delicious with tofu and scallions! Fresh garlic and seaweed with fresh sesame seeds and chili oil you couldn't ask for more condiments. With a line that sometimes stretches out the door and only two tablets for ordering it can be a little hectic but maybe adding in more ordering stations could help alleviate that or maybe it's on purpose to control orders. Whelp! It's a great spot for late night ramen</text>

<rating>5<//rating><Text>Just finished brunch at Tatsu, the local hip Ramen place in town.

Pros:

Delicious, complex broth

Many Vegan (or Vegetarian) options

Free extras, like Soft Boiled Eggs and Corn

Every bowl has an anime strip on the side ‚Äì fun to read!

Cheap for what it is, great quantity/quality

Noodles are soft yet plump

Black Garlic Oil makes the broth distinctively good

High quality meats for those meat eaters

Order from your Ipad from outside the restaurant, then come pick it up in 15 min or less!

Free parking nearby

Cons:

Small seating, sometimes staff get confused by whose first in line< /Text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP1Ox6vnDym03D9YE3ZbD3VR2Az8WAIx2Fi3Qdu=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMFeg9oN46vBXEKKwm_yvRENC62jcqEBbk5t2Yq=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures>< Resp>

< review>
Ate here for the first time last year. There was a huge line of customers waiting for them to open & that drew my attention. Service was quick and accurate. I ordered the Bold Ramen and the Pork Bun. Let me say, it was easily one of best meals I've ever had. So flavorful, savory, and it was the perfect portion size. Yesenia, Chris, and Adam provided amazing customer service. I recommend coming here early and if you're unsure of what to get, ask the staff what they recommend or for a list of the popular dishes. I make it a point to stop here as often as I can if I'm in LA.</review>

<review>This review is based on both past experiences, and my experience from last night. First off, Tatsu Ramen is so delicious, I cant have Ramen at any other place without dreaming of Tatsu's Soul Ramen. The long line curving around the building is typically worth it. Or at least it was, once before.

Last time was not worth it whatsoever, and I wish I was aware of this before I brought my friend, from the other side of the country visiting for like only half the day, to bring to Tatsu for their vegan options. Huuge mistake and I don't plan to make it again until something changes. After 70 minutes of waiting in line, we made it to the door. The rest of the line was a cattle-crunch filling the small space that leads to iPads to order from. Thought it would be a good idea to place my order to-go instead, as that line was open, and maybe, just maybe, it would be quicker? Nope, it was another hour and a half, after already waiting 70 minutes. Here's the worst part though. Half the seats were empty, and half the kitchen was open. How is a restaurant this successful so understaffed?!? Are they not aware how successful they are? Big honchos are absolutely rolling in dough, can't tell me they're not aware. There's been a Hiring sign up for as long as I can remember, and I don't see it anymore, definitely needs to go back up. I ended up getting a refund and my friend had to leave for LAX hungry. Ended up eating food elsewhere at 10:50 when I got to Tatsu at 7:20.

I see Tatsu has opened up in Pasadena, I'll be checking that out very soon. I recommend a Tatsu in Silver Lake and in North Hollywood. It's clear people like Tatsu and are willing to travel far to get it, it's time to bring it to them.<//review>< pics>

< Review>
The worst dining experience I had in Los Angeles was at Tatsu Ramen on Melrose.  It's basically located in a strip mall, and my understanding is people will stand in line for this place. Thankfully, there wasn't a line the night we went. You enter and are guided to a bank of iPads where you place your order and are then prompted by the iPad to include a tip. I'm immediately put off, this restaurant has already done less for me than a cashier at McDonalds. No tip! You run your own card and turn to the left where there is a ma√Ætre 'd type person behind a black strap/velvet rope situation. He lifts the rope and motions to the tiny dining area full of those horrid communal tables, "Seat Yourself".  Your food and beverage is brought out and we are told they will be around to refill beverages, my friends and I take turns throughout the visit searching for someone who will refill the beverages for us.  In the end I paid $15.00 for a bowl of broth with noodles, a hard boiled egg and three tiny thin strips of chicken. I could have made this at home and it would have been just as tasty (and I'm someone who doesn't really cook)  I understand there are other locations and perhaps those are better.< /Review>

< userid>
112921105189982859876</userid>
<username>Susanna Osman< /username>< Time>
1569502888758<//Time>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
Been here multiple times and it never disappoints me or my friends.  Coming back from Japan, I was really looking for a place that I can have some ramen that doesn't seem like I got it out of a foam cup.  Tatsu is my go to.

Are they usually busy? yes, is it worth the little bit of wait? good things come to those who wait! But really, it goes by quite fast.  Ramen is meant to be eaten right away, you don't sit and chill.

I loved the soul ramen, noodles are considerably fresh, the broth is fantastic, and I love that you can choose your ingredients based off of your taste, so it is perfectly catered to you. oh and the wagyu burger is awesome, I would even recommend getting it as a side and sharing it with someone.

My only complaint is that they don't have a spicy option, or none that I have noticed, and the sauce you may ask for isn't very spicy.  Other than that, enjoy the ramen, and enjoy the little writings in the bowl...shhh</review>

<Name>Ashton Sherer< /Name>< Text>
There was a long line on a hot day. It took about forty minutes just to finally get seated. The nice thing is that you order from mounted tablets while you're in line, and then they seat you so you get your food pretty quickly. We had a group of 12, but the largest table they had was an 8-seater. That wasn't a problem for us, but it's good to know that this is a medium-sized place. Not too small and not too big.  I had the red ramen and it was wonderful, but way too much for me. There's a surprise if you can get all the way down to the bottom of the ramen bowl. I will definitely visit this restaurant again.<//Text>

The food is delicious! We ordered a couple bowls and veggie fried rice. We received our bowls no longer after we sat down and that the fried rice was coming soon. It never came. I mentioned it to a waiter and I saw him go tell the kitchen. About 15 minutes later, after seeing several rice bowls get pushed out, we still didn't get ours. We were debating wether to ask for a refund at this point but we decided to give it a bit more time. Then I heard a cook from the kitchen say, "here's for the crying people" (in Spanish) not knowing he was talking about us. That bowl of rice stayed on the counter until 5 minutes later when a waiter grabbed it and brought it to our table. At this point we were pretty much done with our food. We asked to get the rice to go instead.

I understand if it's busy and the staff loses track of things but this time it wasn't, the comment that the cook said, plus leaving the rice just sitting there for 5 minutes and taking more than 15 minutes overall just for one veggie fried rice is unacceptable. Usually the staff is great but this shift was not and after this experience, I won't be taking my family there anymore.

Tatsu Ramen, thank you for your service. Continue making delicious food. Careful when hiring new staff.<//Review>

103528048120161655910< /userid>
<user_name>Rebekah Powell</user_name><Date>1534892605528</Date><rating>4<//rating>< text>
The food is excellent, but your appetite needs to come paired with patience! Long waits at both Tatsu locations, especially on weekends.  If loud and bustling is your thing, this is a great spot for dining in. If that's not your scene, order online for takeout, but expect to wait up to 2 hours for your food to be ready for pickup, and for it to take longer than the estimated time you when you order. That said, I've never been disappointed by a meal at Tatsu, and keep coming back despite the occasional hassle. It's worth the wait!< /text>

I've been here a few times before and really enjoyed my experience, but last night was sadly disappointing. My vegan ramen had no flavor aside from raw onion, my boyfriend & I couldn't enjoy sitting on the patio because somebody was smoking a cigar (staff did nothing about it), the bathroom was filthy, as were pretty much all the tables, and I had to grab a pitcher myself to fill our own water because it was late on a Monday night &   it seemed like nobody really cared about what was going on with diners, in favor of rushing their closing procedures so they could go home. Good luck Tatsu, you have lots of potential.< /text>

This was my first ever ramen "experience". We arrived around 8-9 and there was a line out the door and to the street. It moved fairly quickly. I removed a star from my 5 star rating though because the area where you enter your order on the iPad and then wait to be seated is pretty narrow and if it were wider, then people could move out of the way so the other people behind can punch in their orders. But other than that small "snag", the food was great and service was quick and accommodating!</text>

<userid>100048475316570317386</userid>< username>
Jessica W< /username>
<Time>1495175692547<//Time><rating>5< /rating>< review>
This is one of my favorite restaurants in LA! You'll order on an iPad as you enter and then take your receipt to the hostess who will seat you. You may have to wait for a table but the line usually moves quickly and it's worth the wait.

The noodles are fresh, soft boiled eggs perfectly cooked, and I love the extra garlic and chili oil on the tables!

Park in the rear...you get the first hour free and $3 for each hour after. It's a tight lot but the valet knows how to work it so just let him park your car if it's packed.<//review>

<Time>1554335950695< /Time><rate>5<//rate>< review>
This was my first time here so the process was kinda confusing since no one really said anything, haha. The seats are somewhat limited here but the ramen was good! You get in line first and order on the tablet. Once you make your order, then you'll be seated by a host. The food came out fairly quickly but the ramen wasn't HOT HOT. I got the Bold Ramen and it was super flavorful and in my opinion a tad bit too salty. The noodles are thin and chewy. They also give a good amount of meat. Also don't forget to order free corn or spinach onto your noodles. They also have garlic that you can mash into your soup which adds even more to your soup. Would love to come back!< /review>

I often dream about their Bold Ramen. No better place for satisfying that ramen hunger.

Except when you're on a date! Be prepared to wait 30-45 minutes for your food and even more if you'd like to sit inside on a busy weekend evening.

Fresh noodles, great soup, tried the old skool ramen and it's a traditional tonkotsu soup, it resembled the Hakata style ramen , got there at 930pm on a Friday and waited for about an hour for a table. <Text>My experience at Tatsu was impeccable. The concept of the place is pretty neat. When you first walk in, you‚Äôll enter your order on an iPad. I find this very convenient because it avoids human error, saves time and it allows you to customize your bowl of ramen to your own liking. After you‚Äôve entered your order onto the iPad, you‚Äôll receive a printed receipt and then you wait for a host to greet/seat you. We came around 3pm so there wasn‚Äôt a long wait. Our host Liz was very impressive, she was very fast and efficient. We ordered a few sides, the Japanese soft soda (super neat drink), 2 bold ramen noodles, a naked ramen and a soul ramen. The sides were delicious and the portions are generous. We got the red rice, chashu rice and 2 juice pork buns. The ramen was cooked to perfection. The bold ramen broth was very tasty (my favourite!). I can‚Äôt wait to come back and I hope they expand to Toronto in the near future. I highly recommend checking this spot out!< /Text>< Pics>

< Review>
I love Tatsu, favorite ramen place in LA so far. I get the bold (a spicy bowl with broth) with chicken. I've tried their two highest spice levels. Honestly, the highest spice level felt a bit too grainy with all the spices, great taste just not ideal texture. Easily still a 5* rating, overall. The ramen burger is SO GOOD. You can order from little tablets, super easy. The only thing that stinks is the parking situation, depending on when you go.</Review>

< review>
Ordered the hippy (vegan) ramen and added a soft boiled egg. The broth was delicious and the toppings and noodles were well prepared. My only gripe and reason I gave 3 stars is the wait time. I went into the restaurant and ordered to go. I placed my order at 7:50pm and did not walk out until 8:46pm. And it's a bit pricey.<//review>

< review>
I love this restaurant. I usually get the pork ramen, the portions are perfect. The broth is very tasty.  The one sad part is I love the chicken dumplings but they cost more than a bowl of ramen! They do give you a lot though. Maybe if they came with two different portion options I don't need 12 dumplings if I am eating alone. I have also had the pho and it is also very tasty. The chicken can be a bit dry.This is my go to ramen spot in town.</review>

They have ipads in the area where you wait in line so you can  order your food while you're in line. They also have an area with glass windows where you can see the guy making ramen. Once you get to the to the front of the line the waitress will seat your group. I ordered the Soul Ramen. It was about $12. The broth was pretty salty but the flavor is there. 1530438697434< /time>
<Rating>2</Rating><review>Good ramen, but very bad service.

I used to love going to this ramen place because that's how good it is and the customer service was ok. Seems like the employees don't care for you once you have got your food. Their ramen is made from scratch.  Their broth is very rich in flavor.

I normally get the bold ramen. What I like is you get to choose how much spice, any greens and how much as well as garlic, and either chicken, pork or one other kind. Also, if you want the egg or not. I normally like to order corn on the side, but the last couple of times they never bring it out. I do ask for it and sometimes if you seating outside, good luck on getting any employee to come out.

<gmap_id>0x80c2bf2ab548da49:0xb5e3296938e1d959< /gmap_id><text>Was craving some Ramen while visiting LA so we were recommended this place. Of course it also had a lot of reviews on yelp as well. The place is located on a very busy street and the parking is terrible... but that's just LA for you but people still swarm here! So the concept is really cool because as you walk in there's this area where you can see the guy making fresh ramen noodles. It's really cool. I mean I've seen it in Japan and their technique is different and legit authentic but it's still good to know the ramen is made in house and not out of a prepackaged bag. So the ordering system is self serve through a tech savvy electric device similar to an iPad. You pick the type of ramen you like which there is like maybe 6 options depending on broth (ie. Light, heavy, vegan) and you can add more toppings and change the spiciness and what not... then you can add side dishes, a drink and buy merchandise. You pay with your credit card and it prints out a ticket. There's a hostess at the end of the line and you seat yourself. The food is made and delivered to you. It's really casual ambience. Seating inside and out. We came at such a perfect time because it wasn't as busy. We sat outside because it was cooler out with a slight breeze. I guess the heat from the kitchen and warm bodies inside made it slightly warmer inside.

Overall, I would try this place again. The price is a bit more than the other place that I love but it's still affordable for a bowl of ramen. Just FYI not a good place to go with a big group of friends bc you can't sit together bc of the concept seat yourself but it's nice and fast for like a quick bite and be on your way. Also parking is a pain in the butt for side parking in the neighborhood.</text><Date>1531852470180</Date><userid>108192155048283042115< /userid>< rating>

<Review>Was craving some Ramen while visiting LA so we were recommended this place. Of course it also had a lot of reviews on yelp as well. The place is located on a very busy street and the parking is terrible... but that's just LA for you but people still swarm here! So the concept is really cool because as you walk in there's this area where you can see the guy making fresh ramen noodles. It's really cool. I mean I've seen it in Japan and their technique is different and legit authentic but it's still good to know the ramen is made in house and not out of a prepackaged bag. So the ordering system is self serve through a tech savvy electric device similar to an iPad. You pick the type of ramen you like which there is like maybe 6 options depending on broth (ie. Light, heavy, vegan) and you can add more toppings and change the spiciness and what not... then you can add side dishes, a drink and buy merchandise. You pay with your credit card and it prints out a ticket. There's a hostess at the end of the line and you seat yourself. The food is made and delivered to you. It's really casual ambience. Seating inside and out. We came at such a perfect time because it wasn't as busy. We sat outside because it was cooler out with a slight breeze. I guess the heat from the kitchen and warm bodies inside made it slightly warmer inside.

Overall, I would try this place again. The price is a bit more than the other place that I love but it's still affordable for a bowl of ramen. Just FYI not a good place to go with a big group of friends bc you can't sit together bc of the concept seat yourself but it's nice and fast for like a quick bite and be on your way. Also parking is a pain in the butt for side parking in the neighborhood.</Review>< Rate>

< Review>
The staff here are very friendly and helpful, I took my pug with me and dined at the patio, the lovely waitresses offered a bowl of water for him. The flavor of the soup and meat (I had the Soul ramen with pork) is top quality and very tasty.

However, the ramen noodles themselves aren't made on the spot, you can actually see the batches of noodles stacked on top of each other through the glass when you wait in line to order, and the texture is bit too hard and not chewy at all (minus ‚≠ê here). Ingredients are sort of lacking, for a $14.5 bowl of ramen there is no bamboo shoots or egg included.

I am not going to complain about finding parking or the extra long wait time, but minus another ‚≠ê for the strong smell of rotten rags in the hand washing area. It almost took my appetite away.< /Review>

<username>Ben C<//username><text>I am very surprised to see many good reviews this ramen place received. I went there with my wife after reading its yelp and good reviews. The ramen tasted ok but not something exceptional. What really disappointed us was its ridiculously inefficient service. Their iPad pre-ordering system is pointless because you would still end up waiting in line for an hour before they seat you. That's not because they have limited seating, but because it took forever for them to clean up empty tables to seat the customers waiting in line. There were at least three empty tables when we waited and it took them 15 minutes to actually utilize the tables. High tech poor execution is what they are. And after an hour of wait, we were finally seated. It took another 15 minutes for the food to come. What's the point of pre-ordering again, we wondered. We will never recommend this place to any of our friends.</text></record>

<Pics>None</Pics><username>ben der<//username><GmapID>0x80c2bf2ab548da49:0xb5e3296938e1d959</GmapID><text>WHAT DID I GET:  The Bold Ramen and the Wagyu Ramen Burger.

HOW WAS IT:  The Bold Ramen was...adequate.  It wasn't terrible but it wasn't great, and to be honest, I have no idea what everyone's talking about when they say this place is 'one of the best ramen places in LA.'  It's okay, but it's far from being 'the best.'  Truthfully, I've had packaged ramen with more flavorful broth and noodles.

The Wagyu Ramen Burger was just terrible.  Bad, bad, bad.  First of all, it doesn't look anything like the picture on the menu; the ramen noodle patties are super thin, and the burger is drenched in this kind of weird overly-powerful BBQ sauce.  As for the taste, it was so unbelievably salty, I had to send this thing back.  It was seriously like biting into a big pile of salt; after one bite, I had to down two whole glasses of water.

HOW MUCH DID IT COST:  Including tip, it was $16.15.  They took off the price of the burger, because I sent it back.  But still, $12 for a medium-sized bowl of mediocre ramen is just way too overpriced.

WOULD I COME BACK/RECOMMEND THIS PLACE:  No and no.  The food was mediocre to terrible, and the service wasn't too great either.  The guy who 'helped' me with the refund had no idea what he was talking about and he made the whole refund process ridiculously complicated.

If they had any integrity at all, they would've comp'ed the whole thing to make up for my terrible experience with their food and service.  SMH.

If you're craving ramen in LA, you're seriously better off making your own at home rather than coming to this place.  I really don't understand how this place has gotten so many positive reviews; my only guess is that the people who raved about this place were so drunk and hungry at the time, anything would've tasted amazing to them.  But if you're NOT drunk or starving, you're probably not going to have a great time here.</text>< date>

<user_name>Parker G<//user_name><Gmap_id>0x80c2bf2ab548da49:0xb5e3296938e1d959< /Gmap_id>< Pics>
None</Pics>
< text>
Tatsu Ramen wins a stamp of approval for being excellent where it matters most - the ramen.  The horrible system for waiting for a seat and ordering food almost turned me off from even staying, however.  The line goes out the door, mainly because the seating is very limited and the ordering system is extremely poorly organized.  Once inside, they have three iPads that you use to select the food items that you want, and then you can pay with credit card.  The iPad failed to process any of my cards, however, and people behind me in line were streaming past me.  I had to select cash and pay later.  You then have to continue to wait in line, after having been cut by multiple people because of the organization of the iPads ruining the order of who was first in line, and wait to be seated.  The tables are all communal in nature, and needless to say I was rather frustrated by the time I was finally seated.  They then lost my order somehow and never brought it out, so I went and asked about it and they quickly made it for me and promptly brought it out.  The food itself was wonderful, the ramen was very good, nothing amazing, but about as good as the ramen I've had at other places in LA.  The whole ordeal of ordering, waiting, and finally getting the food was too tenuous and ridiculous to give a better review, unfortunately.  Although good, I'll be going to other Ramen places with comparatively good ramen and a much better system in place for ordering and seating.< /text>

3</Rating>

< rating>
3<//rating>
<text>Tatsu Ramen wins a stamp of approval for being excellent where it matters most - the ramen.  The horrible system for waiting for a seat and ordering food almost turned me off from even staying, however.  The line goes out the door, mainly because the seating is very limited and the ordering system is extremely poorly organized.  Once inside, they have three iPads that you use to select the food items that you want, and then you can pay with credit card.  The iPad failed to process any of my cards, however, and people behind me in line were streaming past me.  I had to select cash and pay later.  You then have to continue to wait in line, after having been cut by multiple people because of the organization of the iPads ruining the order of who was first in line, and wait to be seated.  The tables are all communal in nature, and needless to say I was rather frustrated by the time I was finally seated.  They then lost my order somehow and never brought it out, so I went and asked about it and they quickly made it for me and promptly brought it out.  The food itself was wonderful, the ramen was very good, nothing amazing, but about as good as the ramen I've had at other places in LA.  The whole ordeal of ordering, waiting, and finally getting the food was too tenuous and ridiculous to give a better review, unfortunately.  Although good, I'll be going to other Ramen places with comparatively good ramen and a much better system in place for ordering and seating.< /text>< pics>

<review>This is like the more fun, younger brother to Tsujita Annex. 4 stars because it is great all-around but doesn't have the knock-my-socks-off intense maturity of the  Tsujita broth BUT all other factors are fantastic and I would still go here over any of the generic places in L.A.

My go-to: The Bold

Taste- 5/5 This broth is also not typical like Daikokuya or other commonly popular ramen places. There is a richness and depth that I appreciate.
Service- 5/5 The ipad ordering system decreases mistakes and increases efficiency. Tip is anonymous and on the way out so there's no pressure but don't be a scrooge. Most of us live on tips in this town.
Value- 5/5 Great price for this quality ramen. I never leave hungry.

This is the second location. Initially, the broth and menu weren't as good as the one on Sawtelle but last I checked in Jan 2016, they've worked themselves out and remain my 2nd favorite.

There is a teeny tiny parking lot that turns into 1-hour free valet during peak hours.<//review>< pictures>
None< /pictures>

< name>
Tim C</name>
< userid>
101834869821831241701</userid>
< Review>
When a friend invites you for a visit to the soft opening, yes please! Thanks to Aya T., my media savvy blogging friend says, "you fly, I'll buy". What better deal can you get?

Navigating through the streets of LA, you cannot miss the huge Dragon mural on the East wall of this building. That should tell you, it's right here, stop, park and get your butt over here. Warm greetings as we walk in through the front doors, we are directed to the iPads on the wall for the ordering process. "We will be taking care of your tab today" is what I heard, (rub hands together like I have an evil plan brewing). Pay by credit cards or cash and present your receipt to the wait staff to be seated, that's the typical process after the soft opening. This is definitely a place fit to be on Melrose as I look around how beautiful the space is decorated. Menu even made for "hipsters" and "vegans".

We sat right at the end of the bar area overlooking the kitchen. It's like watching musicians putting a great bowl together working in harmony as they communicate like a melody. Another person works the rice and the pork buns while other things are happening in the background.

The rice bowls arrive, then the pork bun, ramen bowls, drinks, sensory overload, what do I take a picture of first? What do I taste first? Here's what happened when I started with the Soul ramen, (pause for the mmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm sound effects) which is their signature bowl.  This bowl has lots of flavor attributed by black garlic oil playing with the tonkatsu broth. I know that's what I want to order again. Bold ramen has the same broth with definitive ingredients for the heat you can tell with the red color but pales in taste in my opinion. Being able to order a wide variety, the same seasoned pork is used for the rice bowl and the pork bun. The taste difference in with the rice or on a bun, I already know I want my own pork bun on the next visit.

It was very interesting speaking with one of the waiters. Kyle had the same idea, we all agree dessert is missing from this great menu. Something to end a great bowl of ramen or two would definitely round things out. I'm happy to hear different experiences when they were in Japan, the order process is very similar. Walk up to a machine, punch in everything, hand your order over to the chef. I will be updating this review as I will be trying another bowl soon.< /Review>
<Rating>5<//Rating></record>

<Review>I came here on a Wed night when I was done with the bars I noticed it with the open late sign. Cool I said I love open late spots. Upon parking and entering I noticed instead of the normal ramen experience where people say Hello and Goodbye with the standard greeting you are greeted by a wall with screens. I felt very alone, now to be honest the ordering was very easy but there was a person who took my ipad order ticket, why not just order from that guy? My friend asked me. Upon sitting ourselves down I glanced at the wall and saw some generic 4k footage on loop on a huge tv and I also realized there was much i. The way of music it felt very lonely, like being alone in space. Aside from the water person asking if we needed water the other employees just ignored us. The ramen itself was not that good either the broth didn't seem as rich as Diakokuya or Shin Sen Gumi or Silverlake Ramen which Id been to before. The egg was who instead of cut in half like every other place Ive been. Overall it felt like a waste of time but id you've never had ramen before you may like it.<//Review><time>1412981763409<//time><Name>Nicholas A<//Name>< Pictures>

It ‚Äôs efficient to say and leads to maximizing the profits of the store. There is no waste, it is easy to understand and is fashionable. It's also great to have cashless ordering and payments before sitting on an iPad.

The taste of ramen itself is moderate compared to Japan, but it is high in the United States. There are few toppings and the price is average in the US. The char siu bowl is sweet rice with a lot of water and cooked with plenty of water.

All of the shops are full of commitment to win and succeed in the United States. A fairly high level store.

Personally, I liked ‚ÄúCheeky Ramen‚Äù the most. Other tastes are not bad, but the taste is unclear. It ‚Äôs more like the flavor of ramen in the United States.

It's free until 3 o'clock in the middle of the night, and I went to near 12:00 in the middle of the night, but it was full. However, I sat down in about 10 minutes. Evidence of great operation with short waiting time.

This is a great shop
